Like the whole storm
troopers always failing

00:33:52.970 --> 00:33:54.740
to actually hit their targets?

00:33:54.740 --> 00:33:59.300
Or having some comedy part of
that of the usual adventure

00:33:59.300 --> 00:34:02.400
troupes of Indiana Jones and
all these movies that you are--

00:34:02.400 --> 00:34:02.930
STEVEN SCAIA: Yeah
I mean, I think

00:34:02.930 --> 00:34:04.972
because like we were
saying, the show takes place

00:34:04.972 --> 00:34:08.989
in a world where we
literally reference Indiana

00:34:08.989 --> 00:34:10.850
Jones, "Predator,"
"Die Hard," like,

00:34:10.850 --> 00:34:14.630
all those movies that you'd
love if you loved the show.

00:34:14.630 --> 00:34:16.190
And so it gives
you a chance to be

00:34:16.190 --> 00:34:19.023
able to not just
take those moments

00:34:19.023 --> 00:34:20.190
and turn them on their head.

00:34:20.190 --> 00:34:21.860
But actually
acknowledge the moment

00:34:21.860 --> 00:34:24.960
when you're doing something
from one of those movies.

00:34:24.960 --> 00:34:26.929
Two characters can look
at be like, oh my god.

00:34:26.929 --> 00:34:28.570
We're totally doing this
thing from that thing.

00:34:28.570 --> 00:34:29.280
It's like, oh my god.

00:34:29.280 --> 00:34:29.960
This is awesome.

00:34:29.960 --> 00:34:33.380
And I think it is really fun
because it feels like people

00:34:33.380 --> 00:34:34.969
I'd want to hang out with.

00:34:34.969 --> 00:34:36.552
MATTHEW FEDERMAN:
Yeah I think for us,

00:34:36.552 --> 00:34:39.290
the trick is like, if it ever
becomes so meta that it's goofy

00:34:39.290 --> 00:34:42.112
and that it's like you're not
watching the show anymore.

00:34:42.112 --> 00:34:44.570
You're watching us all making
a show, you know what I mean?

00:34:44.570 --> 00:34:46.310
Like, then we don't
want to go that far.

00:34:46.310 --> 00:34:49.820
But we want to go far
enough where if literally

00:34:49.820 --> 00:34:52.230
you were in this
situation, wouldn't you

00:34:52.230 --> 00:34:53.480
bring up "Die Hard" right now?

00:34:53.480 --> 00:34:54.320
Like, wouldn't-- you
know what I mean?

00:34:54.320 --> 00:34:55.159
It's like we all--

00:34:55.159 --> 00:34:58.280
because it's partially a
show about culture and things

00:34:58.280 --> 00:35:00.818
like that as art
and antiquities are.

00:35:00.818 --> 00:35:02.360
And pop culture is
a part of culture.

00:35:02.360 --> 00:35:04.568
So it's like, it's the way
we all talk to each other.

00:35:04.568 --> 00:35:06.080
And their characters--

00:35:06.080 --> 00:35:10.068
Lexi like, doesn't know
any of his references.

00:35:10.068 --> 00:35:11.610
Because she grew up
around the world.

00:35:11.610 --> 00:35:14.117
She wasn't, you know, so
it's like, the pop culture

00:35:14.117 --> 00:35:16.700
references in the show actually
serve another purpose of like,

00:35:16.700 --> 00:35:18.800
being able to talk about
culture in a different way

00:35:18.800 --> 00:35:19.925
and all that kind of stuff.

00:35:19.925 --> 00:35:22.700
So I think when we're
deconstructing the genre,

00:35:22.700 --> 00:35:25.230
we're deconstructing
it like modernize it,

00:35:25.230 --> 00:35:27.197
but we're not deconstructing
it so far that it

00:35:27.197 --> 00:35:28.280
feels like it falls apart.

00:35:30.840 --> 00:35:33.300
SPEAKER 6: I do follow before.

00:35:33.300 --> 00:35:35.450
So now concerning talking
that you folks are--

00:35:35.450 --> 00:35:38.250
you mentioned about, oh we
want to use, like, you know,

00:35:38.250 --> 00:35:41.510
right now, sort of ISIS
as a model of they're

00:35:41.510 --> 00:35:43.640
dealing with art, and you
know, before the Nazis.

00:35:43.640 --> 00:35:45.480
There's no Nazis anymore.

00:35:45.480 --> 00:35:47.750
Do we plan to then
maybe for other seasons

00:35:47.750 --> 00:35:51.290
use other sort of like, the
narcos in Latin America?

00:35:51.290 --> 00:35:52.690
Or warlords in Africa?

00:35:52.690 --> 00:35:55.040
And like, making it a
little more diverse,

00:35:55.040 --> 00:35:57.727
and less just, you
know, Islam, bad.

00:35:57.727 --> 00:35:58.560
And stuff like that.

00:35:58.560 --> 00:36:01.185
STEVEN SCAIA: That's exactly how
we think about the show, which

00:36:01.185 --> 00:36:02.995
is in success, were we
did do more seasons,

00:36:02.995 --> 00:36:05.120
we would pick a different
part of the world with it

00:36:05.120 --> 00:36:07.250
maybe a different treasure,
different bad guys.

00:36:07.250 --> 00:36:09.120
And they would want
a different thing.

00:36:09.120 --> 00:36:12.830
But I think that like any good
summer novel or blockbuster

00:36:12.830 --> 00:36:14.690
in the franchise
of it, we want you

00:36:14.690 --> 00:36:19.610
to be able to look at the visual
and know, oh this is a Season 2

00:36:19.610 --> 00:36:20.660
episode.

00:36:20.660 --> 00:36:22.070
This is a Season 3 episode.

00:36:22.070 --> 00:36:24.100
Because of where they
are in the world.

00:36:24.100 --> 00:36:25.886
MATTHEW FEDERMAN:
And we also the--

00:36:25.886 --> 00:36:28.280
when we pitched the show, we
were talking about how like,

00:36:28.280 --> 00:36:32.480
in real life, there's guys with
AK-47s in parts of the world

00:36:32.480 --> 00:36:34.400
like, you know, the
ancient city of Palmyra

00:36:34.400 --> 00:36:35.932
was blown up by ISIS.

00:36:35.932 --> 00:36:38.140
So those guys that went in
there, they killed people.

00:36:38.140 --> 00:36:39.530
They cut stuff out.

00:36:39.530 --> 00:36:40.785
They put it on a truck.

00:36:40.785 --> 00:36:42.410
Then they blow up
the rest of the stuff

00:36:42.410 --> 00:36:44.408
that they can't
move for PR value.

00:36:44.408 --> 00:36:45.200
They're like, look.

00:36:45.200 --> 00:36:46.880
We're the guys who
did this thing.

00:36:46.880 --> 00:36:50.008
Then all that stuff goes into
like a free port somewhere.

00:36:50.008 --> 00:36:51.800
So we have a free port
in our first episode

00:36:51.800 --> 00:36:55.100
because we're like, we are
kind of paralleling real world

00:36:55.100 --> 00:36:55.600
stuff.

00:36:55.600 --> 00:36:57.628
We're just making it awesome.

00:36:57.628 --> 00:36:59.670
But and trying to not be
completely [INAUDIBLE]..

00:36:59.670 --> 00:37:02.480
But it is actually the
path that this stuff takes,

00:37:02.480 --> 00:37:05.700
which is, it will go to a
free port, which is a, like a,

00:37:05.700 --> 00:37:08.600
you know, somewhere in
Geneva or something.

00:37:08.600 --> 00:37:10.962
It's a place where the stuff
comes in, it's not taxed.

00:37:10.962 --> 00:37:12.420
No one actually
knows what's there.

00:37:12.420 --> 00:37:14.000
There's literally like,
billions and billions

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:14.460
of dollars of art--

00:37:14.460 --> 00:37:15.980
STEVEN SCAIA: It's a
Swiss bank for stuff.

00:37:15.980 --> 00:37:16.897
MATTHEW FEDERMAN: Yes.

00:37:16.897 --> 00:37:19.370
And then that stuff
will come out like,

00:37:19.370 --> 00:37:21.370
10 years from now
when the heat is off.

00:37:21.370 --> 00:37:24.980
And it will end up on the walls
of a very wealthy person's

00:37:24.980 --> 00:37:26.510
house or in a museum.

00:37:26.510 --> 00:37:29.060
And you know, so it's
like, there's not just

00:37:29.060 --> 00:37:30.437
like one bad guy in that story.

00:37:30.437 --> 00:37:31.520
There's a lot of bad guys.

00:37:31.520 --> 00:37:34.280
Because if someone wasn't
paying for that stuff, then ISIS

00:37:34.280 --> 00:37:37.190
wouldn't be using it
to fund killing people.

00:37:37.190 --> 00:37:39.830
And so, wherever we
are in the world,

00:37:39.830 --> 00:37:41.450
or whatever the
season is, it's always

00:37:41.450 --> 00:37:45.092
this like intersection of people
doing really bad things-- they

00:37:45.092 --> 00:37:47.300
could be criminal networks,
they could be terrorists.

00:37:47.300 --> 00:37:50.840
And then how that ends up in
places of wealth and privilege.

00:37:50.840 --> 00:37:52.940
And how like, they
completely ignore the fact

00:37:52.940 --> 00:37:54.750
that the other end of this,
there's a lot of bodies there.

00:37:54.750 --> 00:37:56.660
And then our people are
following that trail.

00:37:56.660 --> 00:37:58.080
So we're in dangerous places.

00:37:58.080 --> 00:37:59.163
But we're also in tuxedos.

00:37:59.163 --> 00:38:00.955
STEVEN SCAIA: And also
we embrace that too,

00:38:00.955 --> 00:38:02.840
where not every rich
person is a good person.

00:38:02.840 --> 00:38:04.258
Not every mobster
is a bad person.

00:38:04.258 --> 00:38:06.050
And that's part of the
fun of the show too,

00:38:06.050 --> 00:38:07.670
of like, as we build
out the treasure

00:38:07.670 --> 00:38:09.980
squad as the season
goes on, it's

00:38:09.980 --> 00:38:12.980
unlikely friends and foes
you wouldn't necessarily

00:38:12.980 --> 00:38:14.447
see coming.

00:38:14.447 --> 00:38:16.780
JOSH LANZET: I think there's
another question over here.

00:38:16.780 --> 00:38:19.630
SPEAKER 7: Yeah, I have
a question for Matt.

00:38:19.630 --> 00:38:23.320
Is there ever tension between
how you want to write the show,

00:38:23.320 --> 00:38:25.360
or what you want to write
about, and like what

00:38:25.360 --> 00:38:30.573
isn't necessary to promote
a good blockbuster TV show?

00:38:30.573 --> 00:38:31.990
MATTHEW FEDERMAN:
I wouldn't say--

00:38:31.990 --> 00:38:36.610
because I think we both have
pretty, pretty broadcast

00:38:36.610 --> 00:38:38.140
sensibilities.

00:38:38.140 --> 00:38:40.630
I think the biggest
tension between us

00:38:40.630 --> 00:38:44.290
is generally a, like once
we figure out, OK, this

00:38:44.290 --> 00:38:46.360
is the story we're
telling, it becomes just

00:38:46.360 --> 00:38:48.580
about knowing what is possible.

00:38:48.580 --> 00:38:50.540
Because I'm not where he is.

00:38:50.540 --> 00:38:52.980
And so, I might think,
like, OK, well we

00:38:52.980 --> 00:38:53.980
can do this whole thing.

00:38:53.980 --> 00:38:55.900
And then he's
like, yeah we don't

00:38:55.900 --> 00:38:57.098
have that location anymore.

00:38:57.098 --> 00:38:57.890
We lost this thing.

00:38:57.890 --> 00:38:58.807
We have to-- you know?

00:38:58.807 --> 00:39:00.860
And then, so sometimes,
he wants to cut a scene.

00:39:00.860 --> 00:39:02.620
And I'm like, that
scene is important

00:39:02.620 --> 00:39:04.060
for the entire season.

00:39:04.060 --> 00:39:05.570
We can't cut that scene.

00:39:05.570 --> 00:39:08.230
But where will you be near,
and we can rewrite the scene

00:39:08.230 --> 00:39:10.300
to fit the place
you're going to be at?

00:39:10.300 --> 00:39:12.310
So our issue is
more generally like

00:39:12.310 --> 00:39:14.210
where the writing
meets the production.

00:39:14.210 --> 00:39:16.240
But in terms of
vision of the show,

00:39:16.240 --> 00:39:19.720
we're pretty much like--
you know, if he is on set

00:39:19.720 --> 00:39:21.555
and somebody is doing something,

00:39:21.555 --> 00:39:23.680
I'm sure there's moments
where he has a thought of,

00:39:23.680 --> 00:39:25.725
Matt would not like if
you said that that way.

00:39:25.725 --> 00:39:28.100
And I will be in the room and
someone will pitch a thing.

00:39:28.100 --> 00:39:29.960
And I'm like, I'm
fine with this story.

00:39:29.960 --> 00:39:33.130
But right now, I am
having like, some

00:39:33.130 --> 00:39:35.770
referred rage from another
place that's entering my body.

00:39:35.770 --> 00:39:37.780
And I think it's like,
Steve is perceiving

00:39:37.780 --> 00:39:39.405
that this story is boring.

00:39:39.405 --> 00:39:41.670
And so we now need
to do something to,

00:39:41.670 --> 00:39:43.270
like, you know,
juice this thing.

00:39:43.270 --> 00:39:44.412
Because you know--

00:39:44.412 --> 00:39:46.120
STEVEN SCAIA: It's a
good-- it's a good--

00:39:46.120 --> 00:39:47.440
because we've known
each other for so long

00:39:47.440 --> 00:39:48.790
and have worked
together for so long,

00:39:48.790 --> 00:39:51.127
we are a good check and balance
against us too, of like,

00:39:51.127 --> 00:39:52.460
we like a lot of the same stuff.

00:39:52.460 --> 00:39:54.830
But there's also stuff that
I like that he doesn't like

00:39:54.830 --> 00:39:55.580
and vice versa.

00:39:55.580 --> 00:39:57.247
So it helps us be
like, as long as we're

00:39:57.247 --> 00:39:59.810
in the Venn diagram of
shit we think is awesome,

00:39:59.810 --> 00:40:01.900
we know we're generally
in the right zone.

00:40:01.900 --> 00:40:03.900
MATTHEW FEDERMAN: Right,
and like, for instance,

00:40:03.900 --> 00:40:06.670
for pop culture references,
I am less interested in them

00:40:06.670 --> 00:40:09.010
except insofar as
they reveal character

00:40:09.010 --> 00:40:11.470
or they reveal like, how
these two people would

00:40:11.470 --> 00:40:13.040
connect to each other.

00:40:13.040 --> 00:40:16.480
But if when shows do references
just so the audience is like,

00:40:16.480 --> 00:40:18.000
oh, they're doing
that thing I know.

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:20.292
And it's like, well, you
don't really earn that moment.

00:40:20.292 --> 00:40:21.940
But so there's times
where we have--

00:40:21.940 --> 00:40:23.990
we have some big moments
in the show where

00:40:23.990 --> 00:40:26.870
there is a pop culture reference
happening right at that moment.

00:40:26.870 --> 00:40:28.000
But what that moment
is about is like,

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:30.167
these two people have now
connected with each other.

00:40:30.167 --> 00:40:32.000
And now they're speaking
the same language.

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:33.792
And so that's where
like, sometimes they'll

00:40:33.792 --> 00:40:37.108
be a reference that I'm like,
this feels very like, in 10

00:40:37.108 --> 00:40:39.650
years, no one's going to know
what this moment means anymore.

00:40:39.650 --> 00:40:42.370
Because it's totally
dependent on a reference

00:40:42.370 --> 00:40:44.300
to understand why
we're seeing it.

00:40:44.300 --> 00:40:47.200
And so I'm like, it needs to
work on its own inherently.

00:40:47.200 --> 00:40:48.790
And then, on top
of that, it can now

00:40:48.790 --> 00:40:51.040
be awesome because someone's
like, oh, from that movie

00:40:51.040 --> 00:40:52.452
I love.

00:40:52.452 --> 00:40:53.910
JOSH LANZET: Were
there-- oh, we've

00:40:53.910 --> 00:40:54.993
got another one over here.

00:40:54.993 --> 00:40:56.202
SPEAKER 8: Hi.

00:40:56.202 --> 00:40:58.160
So you were talking about
how people don't make

00:40:58.160 --> 00:41:00.130
treasure hunter shows anymore.

00:41:00.130 --> 00:41:00.825
Other than this.

00:41:00.825 --> 00:41:02.450
And I think part of
the reason for that

00:41:02.450 --> 00:41:04.220
is that they're very
steeped in this kind

00:41:04.220 --> 00:41:05.803
of like, pre
colonialist, like we just

00:41:05.803 --> 00:41:08.300
go and take stuff and
put it in our museums.

00:41:08.300 --> 00:41:10.340
And similarly--
and on top of that

00:41:10.340 --> 00:41:12.650
now, we have the
whole ISIS aspect.

00:41:12.650 --> 00:41:14.207
And shows which have--

00:41:14.207 --> 00:41:16.040
shows which mention
ISIS tend to make people

00:41:16.040 --> 00:41:20.360
look like who look like me
into terrorists or victims.

00:41:20.360 --> 00:41:23.840
So the question is, do you
spend a lot of time thinking

00:41:23.840 --> 00:41:26.520
about how to subvert
those expectations?

00:41:26.520 --> 00:41:28.515
Cause, I mean, literally
everything does this.

00:41:28.515 --> 00:41:29.390
So I'm wondering if--

00:41:29.390 --> 00:41:30.350
STEVEN SCAIA: Yeah
I mean, that's

00:41:30.350 --> 00:41:33.200
absolutely a big part of how we
thought about the show, which

00:41:33.200 --> 00:41:35.510
is, when we go to places
around the world--

00:41:35.510 --> 00:41:37.820
like there's an episode that
takes place in Casablanca.

00:41:37.820 --> 00:41:39.380
And the cops are good cops.

00:41:39.380 --> 00:41:41.910
And they're trying to
help us solve a problem.

00:41:41.910 --> 00:41:44.690
It's not that it's white
people going to a place

00:41:44.690 --> 00:41:45.903
and saving them.

00:41:45.903 --> 00:41:48.320
It's everybody working together
because we believe in sort

00:41:48.320 --> 00:41:51.080
of the global family of it all.

00:41:51.080 --> 00:41:54.000
Where there are lots of people
from all over the world.

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:55.830
Some people are good,
some people are bad.

00:41:55.830 --> 00:41:57.470
It's not even about
governments necessarily.

00:41:57.470 --> 00:41:58.460
It's about individuals.

00:41:58.460 --> 00:42:01.010
And so I think, even just like,
looking at the two of them

00:42:01.010 --> 00:42:03.290
and seeing how
different they could be.

00:42:03.290 --> 00:42:06.140
But they work together
and they're a great team.

00:42:06.140 --> 00:42:07.610
And that's the core of the show.

00:42:07.610 --> 00:42:10.070
And I think that spills out
for the rest of the show too.

00:42:10.070 --> 00:42:13.610
Where we don't just have all
the white people are good

00:42:13.610 --> 00:42:15.360
and all the not
white people are bad.

00:42:15.360 --> 00:42:18.360
There are good and bad
people all across the world

00:42:18.360 --> 00:42:19.530
at every step of the way.

00:42:19.530 --> 00:42:23.000
And so we moved very consciously
away from our bad guy

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:25.700
being an evil terrorist,
but more-- and also

00:42:25.700 --> 00:42:28.190
try to make Oded Fehr
not be handsome dude

00:42:28.190 --> 00:42:28.940
with amazing hair.

00:42:28.940 --> 00:42:31.070
SOFIA PERNAS: And Lexi's
character is Egyptian.

00:42:31.070 --> 00:42:32.450
She was raised Muslim.

00:42:32.450 --> 00:42:33.920
And we say that in the show.

00:42:33.920 --> 00:42:35.180
I'm actually Muslim.

00:42:35.180 --> 00:42:37.280
And so it was an
interesting convergence

00:42:37.280 --> 00:42:40.910
of characters and real life.

00:42:40.910 --> 00:42:44.343
But yeah, and so the bad guy
of our show killed my father.

00:42:44.343 --> 00:42:46.010
I'm not giving anything
away, because we

00:42:46.010 --> 00:42:47.010
say this in the trailer.

00:42:47.010 --> 00:42:48.110
Just saying.

00:42:48.110 --> 00:42:50.690
But so it's sort of
like, there's no like,

00:42:50.690 --> 00:42:52.760
the bad guy is the Muslim.

00:42:52.760 --> 00:42:56.985
And that's the narrative that we
are going on for seven seasons.

00:42:56.985 --> 00:42:58.610
It's not-- that's
not what this at all.

00:42:58.610 --> 00:43:00.110
STEVEN SCAIA: And that thought
started in the writers room

00:43:00.110 --> 00:43:02.900
where we had a diverse set of
writers from all over the world

00:43:02.900 --> 00:43:03.530
as well.

00:43:03.530 --> 00:43:05.960
Because we wanted to have
that unique perspective that

00:43:05.960 --> 00:43:09.507
isn't two guys who,
you know, live in LA.

00:43:09.507 --> 00:43:11.090
MATTHEW FEDERMAN:
Well the story Steve

00:43:11.090 --> 00:43:12.882
was telling earlier
about the refugee camp,

00:43:12.882 --> 00:43:16.520
it came from two of our
writers were born in Iran

00:43:16.520 --> 00:43:18.830
and then fled in the
revolution and were refugees

00:43:18.830 --> 00:43:19.790
at a certain point.

00:43:19.790 --> 00:43:23.180
And they had pitched a
story, a Casablanca story,

00:43:23.180 --> 00:43:25.520
which to me, was like the
perfect merging of the pop

00:43:25.520 --> 00:43:28.880
culture and the show,
which was, you know,

00:43:28.880 --> 00:43:31.400
he was like, I don't know if
you guys think of it this way.

00:43:31.400 --> 00:43:34.260
But to us, Casablanca
is a refugee story.

00:43:34.260 --> 00:43:35.533
And I was like, it's funny.

00:43:35.533 --> 00:43:36.950
I've never thought
of it that way.

00:43:36.950 --> 00:43:38.947
I've only thought of it
as like, a love story

00:43:38.947 --> 00:43:40.280
or I've thought about the Nazis.

00:43:40.280 --> 00:43:42.990
But they had a very
particular view of it.

00:43:42.990 --> 00:43:46.790
And so they wanted to do this
story where our treasure hunt

00:43:46.790 --> 00:43:48.320
intersects with Casablanca.

00:43:48.320 --> 00:43:50.870
And a lot of the
Casablanca-ness of that movie

00:43:50.870 --> 00:43:54.872
is pervading the episode.

00:43:54.872 --> 00:43:57.080
You know, organically
throughout the story is saying,

00:43:57.080 --> 00:43:59.120
but also, they wanted
to go to a refugee camp

00:43:59.120 --> 00:44:02.570
and they wanted to have
our characters have

00:44:02.570 --> 00:44:05.440
to like, basically take
refuge because the cops are

00:44:05.440 --> 00:44:05.940
after them.

00:44:05.940 --> 00:44:07.140
It's a whole thing.

00:44:07.140 --> 00:44:09.200
But the point is
that, we really wanted

00:44:09.200 --> 00:44:12.520
to tell that story because
especially for, you know,

00:44:12.520 --> 00:44:14.390
a CBS audience,
which is probably

00:44:14.390 --> 00:44:18.360
like the most unlikely
audience to watch--

00:44:18.360 --> 00:44:22.080
or a lot of the things that you
would say are issues, maybe,

00:44:22.080 --> 00:44:24.330
you know, it's a place where
you've seen those issues.

00:44:24.330 --> 00:44:26.810
And we thought, well it
would be great to have

00:44:26.810 --> 00:44:30.320
our characters go there and
really humanize that situation.

00:44:30.320 --> 00:44:34.400
And then, because it's our show
and it's a fun roller coaster,

00:44:34.400 --> 00:44:36.582
we set it on a beach so it
kind of looks attractive.

00:44:36.582 --> 00:44:38.540
But like, the issues that
they're talking about

00:44:38.540 --> 00:44:40.520
are like, they don't
have enough money.

00:44:40.520 --> 00:44:41.945
You know, but they take
these strangers in,

00:44:41.945 --> 00:44:42.590
cause they're like, listen.

00:44:42.590 --> 00:44:44.450
This is a place for people
that don't have a home.

00:44:44.450 --> 00:44:46.040
And we're going to
take you in tonight

00:44:46.040 --> 00:44:47.360
and we're going to protect you.

00:44:47.360 --> 00:44:49.790
STEVEN SCAIA: And another
big part of the show

00:44:49.790 --> 00:44:51.198
is, it's about culture identity.

00:44:51.198 --> 00:44:53.240
So when you go-- we go to
someplace in the world,

00:44:53.240 --> 00:44:54.810
we want to learn
about that place.

00:44:54.810 --> 00:44:56.960
And so there is the
moment in the trailer

00:44:56.960 --> 00:44:58.130
where the pyramid blows up.

00:44:58.130 --> 00:45:00.770
And you could look at that
purely from like the Roland

00:45:00.770 --> 00:45:03.710
Emmerich spectacle of it all
where this thing happens,

00:45:03.710 --> 00:45:05.570
and, oh, isn't
that cool visually?

00:45:05.570 --> 00:45:07.970
But for us, it actually
ripples throughout the show.

00:45:07.970 --> 00:45:11.642
Because it is about the
culture identity of this symbol

00:45:11.642 --> 00:45:12.350
for these people.

00:45:12.350 --> 00:45:14.570
And we had a lot of long
conversations about it.

00:45:14.570 --> 00:45:17.380
We didn't just blow it
up to be controversial.

00:45:17.380 --> 00:45:19.970
We blew it up because we wanted
that to be a thing that people

00:45:19.970 --> 00:45:23.390
could keep coming back to
throughout the show of, no.

00:45:23.390 --> 00:45:25.370
That is what
happens when someone

00:45:25.370 --> 00:45:28.490
who does not respect the culture
of places does this thing.

00:45:28.490 --> 00:45:31.760
And it was a great way to get
people who wouldn't necessarily

00:45:31.760 --> 00:45:33.770
want to help us on our
adventure behind us

00:45:33.770 --> 00:45:35.360
because you could just say, hey.

00:45:35.360 --> 00:45:36.860
You know that thing
at the pyramids?

00:45:36.860 --> 00:45:38.840
That guy we're looking
for, he did that,

00:45:38.840 --> 00:45:40.940
and he is doing this to
your culture right now.

00:45:40.940 --> 00:45:43.357
And we all need to work together
because he took something

00:45:43.357 --> 00:45:44.142
from all of us.

00:45:44.142 --> 00:45:47.840
MATTHEW FEDERMAN: Yeah, so we
were like, basing it on Palmyra

00:45:47.840 --> 00:45:50.460
and the Buddhist statues that
were blown up by ISIS and stuff

00:45:50.460 --> 00:45:50.960
like that.

00:45:50.960 --> 00:45:53.480
Like, when we were thinking
about who is this guy?

00:45:53.480 --> 00:45:54.238
What is he doing?

00:45:54.238 --> 00:45:55.030
Why is he doing it?

00:45:55.030 --> 00:45:56.613
We're trying to use
real world analogs

00:45:56.613 --> 00:45:57.920
to everything that's happening.

00:45:57.920 --> 00:45:59.643
And, you know, when that's--

00:45:59.643 --> 00:46:01.310
and then, interestingly,
we were talking

00:46:01.310 --> 00:46:03.747
about how when the Notre
Dame fire happened,

00:46:03.747 --> 00:46:06.080
and like around the world,
there was a sense of mourning

00:46:06.080 --> 00:46:07.820
of like, this thing
has been there like,

00:46:07.820 --> 00:46:09.590
longer than our country.

00:46:09.590 --> 00:46:11.018
And you know, I
mean, it's a thing

00:46:11.018 --> 00:46:12.560
that you think of
as being permanent.

00:46:12.560 --> 00:46:13.610
STEVEN SCAIA: It's
not just the church.

00:46:13.610 --> 00:46:13.880
MATTHEW FEDERMAN: Right.

00:46:13.880 --> 00:46:14.600
It's not just a church.

00:46:14.600 --> 00:46:15.770
And it means things
to people that

00:46:15.770 --> 00:46:17.210
aren't even of that religion.

00:46:17.210 --> 00:46:19.100
It has a greater
meaning than that.

00:46:19.100 --> 00:46:22.650
And how the world can come
together in moments like that.

00:46:22.650 --> 00:46:25.500
And so we wanted to have
that represented in the show.

00:46:25.500 --> 00:46:30.350
And then also, when Lexi's
character is after revenge,

00:46:30.350 --> 00:46:34.100
and Danny's after some
form of redemption.

00:46:34.100 --> 00:46:36.680
But in the end, there's
also this thing of like,

00:46:36.680 --> 00:46:38.840
if we do this right,
we can kind of

00:46:38.840 --> 00:46:40.430
bring these people
back together again

00:46:40.430 --> 00:46:42.200
and start a process of healing.

00:46:42.200 --> 00:46:44.910
Because we have found
this cultural treasure

00:46:44.910 --> 00:46:46.410
that's been missing
all these years.

00:46:46.410 --> 00:46:47.970
And we can bring it
back to the people.

00:46:47.970 --> 00:46:49.512
So the first part
of your question of

00:46:49.512 --> 00:46:52.920
like, taking things
from that region.

00:46:52.920 --> 00:46:55.040
Like, the classic
line of our genre

00:46:55.040 --> 00:46:56.840
is, that belongs in a museum.

00:46:56.840 --> 00:47:01.010
And so it's interesting to make
the show in, at the time, 2016,

00:47:01.010 --> 00:47:03.710
where it was like, actually,
that's not the right statement

00:47:03.710 --> 00:47:04.210
anymore.

00:47:04.210 --> 00:47:06.747
Like we've moved on from--

00:47:06.747 --> 00:47:09.080
we don't actually think that's
the right answer anymore.

00:47:09.080 --> 00:47:12.560
And if you go to
places like Greece

00:47:12.560 --> 00:47:15.895
where so much of the stuff
was taken out of there.

00:47:15.895 --> 00:47:17.270
And now they have
a museum that's

00:47:17.270 --> 00:47:19.595
at the base of the Parthenon?

00:47:19.595 --> 00:47:20.360
Parthenon, right?

00:47:20.360 --> 00:47:20.930
Yeah.

00:47:20.930 --> 00:47:24.720
And they have all of these
blank spots on the walls where--

00:47:24.720 --> 00:47:27.860
and they have written in, this
is what's supposed to be here.

00:47:27.860 --> 00:47:29.792
It's in this museum in America.

00:47:29.792 --> 00:47:31.250
This is what's
supposed to be here.

00:47:31.250 --> 00:47:32.542
It's in this museum in Germany.

00:47:32.542 --> 00:47:34.700
This is what-- and like,
and what they basically

00:47:34.700 --> 00:47:36.530
said to the world
is, you guys said

00:47:36.530 --> 00:47:38.270
that we couldn't take
care of our stuff.

00:47:38.270 --> 00:47:40.640
Now we've built this
really nice museum.

00:47:40.640 --> 00:47:42.500
Why are you not giving
us our stuff back?

00:47:42.500 --> 00:47:46.220
We built it so it
should be in its home.

00:47:46.220 --> 00:47:49.970
And it's a refrain you hear
several times in the season

00:47:49.970 --> 00:47:53.248
is, that belongs
back in its home.

00:47:53.248 --> 00:47:55.290
We don't talk about it
being in a museum anymore.

00:47:55.290 --> 00:47:58.010
We talk about going back to the
people, you know, of the place

00:47:58.010 --> 00:47:59.380
where it was taken.

00:47:59.380 --> 00:48:01.630
JOSH LANZET: So I know that
we're running out of time.

00:48:01.630 --> 00:48:03.463
So I just want to ask
you one final question

00:48:03.463 --> 00:48:05.870
before we let you guys go.

00:48:05.870 --> 00:48:07.078
Looking forward from--

00:48:07.078 --> 00:48:08.870
I would love to hear
from each of you, what

00:48:08.870 --> 00:48:10.287
are you most excited
for everybody

00:48:10.287 --> 00:48:12.612
to see in Season 1 of
"Blood and Treasure?"

00:48:12.612 --> 00:48:13.820
Without giving too much away.

00:48:16.448 --> 00:48:17.990
SOFIA PERNAS: I'm
most excited to see

00:48:17.990 --> 00:48:21.110
how, the sort of pages
they take from each other's

00:48:21.110 --> 00:48:22.450
books, Lexi and Danny.

00:48:22.450 --> 00:48:25.850
About how they, you know, in
a lot of these two handers

00:48:25.850 --> 00:48:29.090
in these network shows,
you have two people that

00:48:29.090 --> 00:48:31.190
are working together that
are living side by side

00:48:31.190 --> 00:48:32.060
and learning from each other.

00:48:32.060 --> 00:48:34.268
But they never really learn
anything from each other.

00:48:34.268 --> 00:48:37.430
They just remain stubbornly
and rigidly themselves,

00:48:37.430 --> 00:48:38.398
which is not real life.

00:48:38.398 --> 00:48:40.190
I mean, how many times
do your best friends

00:48:40.190 --> 00:48:43.370
that you'll start to adopt
certain mannerisms that they do

00:48:43.370 --> 00:48:47.340
or certain ways that they laugh
or shrug or move their body?

00:48:47.340 --> 00:48:49.880
And I think that's what
I'm most excited about.

00:48:49.880 --> 00:48:52.918
What Lexi learns from
Danny and vice versa.

00:48:52.918 --> 00:48:54.710
MATT BARR: Sort of like
commenting on that,

00:48:54.710 --> 00:48:58.160
saying that, what I really
love most about the script

00:48:58.160 --> 00:49:01.100
was the dynamic between these
two and that kind of push pull.

00:49:01.100 --> 00:49:04.880
It's so fun as an
audience to watch that.

00:49:04.880 --> 00:49:06.620
And it has to be written right.

00:49:06.620 --> 00:49:08.300
And these guys really
did it, you know?

00:49:08.300 --> 00:49:12.170
And I think, rather, just the
movies and shows that I grew up

00:49:12.170 --> 00:49:14.930
on that really did that
most effectively to me

00:49:14.930 --> 00:49:18.725
were, well they were
hits, but they also,

00:49:18.725 --> 00:49:21.690
you know, they're the
things that stick with me.

00:49:21.690 --> 00:49:25.410
And I think that they threaded
that needle really well.

00:49:25.410 --> 00:49:28.230
With these two guys from
different worlds and yet

00:49:28.230 --> 00:49:31.620
somehow they, you know, they
exist in the same space.

00:49:31.620 --> 00:49:35.863
And I'll be damned if they
don't, you know, work.

00:49:35.863 --> 00:49:38.030
MATTHEW FEDERMAN: Yeah I
mean, I love those answers.

00:49:38.030 --> 00:49:40.550
And I feel like
adding to that, I

00:49:40.550 --> 00:49:44.608
think this 13 episodes
tells a whole story.

00:49:44.608 --> 00:49:46.150
And so we're not
asking any questions

00:49:46.150 --> 00:49:48.868
that we're not going to
answer within the 13 episodes.

00:49:48.868 --> 00:49:50.660
And then, hopefully
we'll have more stories

00:49:50.660 --> 00:49:53.790
to tell in the future with these
same characters going forward.

00:49:53.790 --> 00:49:57.520
So to me, I think the way I
want people to go on the journey

00:49:57.520 --> 00:49:59.270
and then see the way
it all comes together

00:49:59.270 --> 00:50:01.490
and see how like, every
line mattered and everything

00:50:01.490 --> 00:50:02.480
that was going on.

00:50:02.480 --> 00:50:04.647
It was all part of one big
story that we're telling.

00:50:04.647 --> 00:50:07.130
So at the end of
the 13, it hopefully

00:50:07.130 --> 00:50:08.930
as a big emotional
impact of like,

00:50:08.930 --> 00:50:11.635
oh this wasn't just a show
about like people running

00:50:11.635 --> 00:50:13.010
